definition.value: A urine abnormality AE that is characterized by when one passes blood sugar (blood glucose) into urine.
A urine abnormality AE that is characterized by an abnormally low urinary specific gravity, i.e., reduced concentration of solutes in the urine.
A urine abnormality AE that is characterized by a medical condition in which ketone bodies are present in the urine.

A urine abnormality AE that is characterized by an abnormal pathologic state in which an excessive amount of myoglobin is found in the urine, imparting a cola-like hue, usually in association with myonecrosis and a clinical picture of weakness, myalgias, edema.
A kidney AE that is characterized by disease or damage of the kidney, which can eventually result in kidney failure

A nephropathy AE that is characterized by any adverse functional or structural changes in the kidney due to the effect of a chemical or biological product that is inhaled, ingested, injected, or otherwise absorbed, or that yields toxic metabolites with an identifiable adverse effect on the kidneys.
A congenital AE that is characterized by a birth defect and inherited condition that affects the urinary tract (kidneys, ureters, and bladder) or the genital tract (reproductive organs).
A urinary system AE that is characterized by the abnormal enlargement of the ureter caused by any blockage that prevents urine from draining into the bladder.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by a condition in which the nephrons, the functional units of the kidneys, become inflamed.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a progressive disease of the kidneys that results from sclerosis (hardening) of the small blood vessels in the kidneys.
A pain AE that is characterized by pain from disease or injury to a kidney

A kidney AE that is characterized by a very heterogeneous group of hereditary and acquired diseases that involve singular or complex dysfunctions of transporters and channels in the renal tubular system
A renal tubular disorder AE that is characterized by acute kidney injury in the renal category involving damage to the tubule cells of the kidneys, which can lead to acute kidney failure
A kidney AE that is characterized by vessel wall leukocyte infiltration, often with necrosis affecting the kidney
A urinary system AE that is characterized by when a person has trouble starting or maintaining a urine stream
A urinary system AE that is characterized by any disorder that affects your urinary tract, which is the body's drainage system for removing urine
A uninary system AE that occurs in bladder
A urine abnormality AE that is characterized by the presence of porphyrins in the urine
An abscess AE that is characterized by an infection that has gotten into the kidneys caused by bacteria.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a kidney disorder where the kidneys are relatively small in comparison to the gender, age, and body weight of the patient.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a sac of fluid that forms in the kidney.
A bladder AE that is characterized by complete absence, or agenesis, of the urinary bladder
A bladder AE that is characterized by a pouch in the bladder wall that a person may either be born with or get later.
A bladder AE that is characterized by scarring and hardening of the tissue in the bladder.
A bladder AE that is characterized by tumor-like formations, projecting above the level of the mucous membrane of the efferent urinary passages, and consisting of granulation tissue.
A bladder AE that is characterized by an enlarged bladder where the bladder walls become thicker and then grow because they are overstretched.
A bladder AE that is characterized by external bladder injuries that are caused by either blunt or penetrating trauma to the lower abdomen, pelvis, or perineum.
A bladder AE that is characterized by squamous metaplasia of the transitional epithelium and keratinization; it is a rare condition.
A bladder AE that is characterized by acute or chronic changes in the uterine shape or position; this can occur in women prior to labor, during labor, or postpartum.
A bladder AE that is characterized by an overly distended bladder with flattened urothelium.
A bladder AE that is characterized by being the putative precursor of urothelial carcinoma in situ (CIS) and invasive urothelial carcinoma of the urinary tract.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a number of urinary conditions in people who lack bladder control due to a brain, spinal cord, or nerve problem.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by a problem that affects the urinary and genital tracts (reproductive organs)
A procedural complication AE that occurs after a blood transfusion
A kidney AE that is characterized by a reversible form of acute renal dysfunction; it encompasses several different conditions that vary considerably.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by an abnormal amount of amino acids in the urine.

A congenital AE that is characterized by a wide range of kidney disease that are from birth; cystic disease may involve one or both kidneys and may or may not occur in the presence of other anomalies.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a bladder whose muscles do not fully contract. This makes it hard to urinate.
A kidney AE that is characterized by a disease that causes abnormal blood clots to form in small blood vessels in the kidneys.
A urinary tract infection AE that is characterized by a type of urinary tract infection caused by bacteria where one or both kidneys become infected.

A urinary system AE that is characterized by the presence of bacteria in urine. It is often accompanied by symptoms is a urinary tract infection while that without is known as asymptomatic bacteriuria.
A bladder neoplasm AE that is characterized by a non-cancerous tumor of the bladder that does not spread (metastasize) to other parts of the body.
A bladder cancer AE that is characterized by cancer that has returned following initial treatment with surgery, radiation, chemotherapy, and immunotherapy.

A bladder AE that is characterized by problems with urination. This may include urgency of urination, frequency of urination, ability to "hold" urine during day or night, urinary incontinence, infrequent voiding, constipation, or other diagnoses.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a blockage at the base or neck of the bladder. Such a blockage reduces or stops the flow of urine into the urethra, which carries urine from the body.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a narrowing that can cause bladder obstruction that leads to incomplete bladder emptying.
A bladder cancer AE that is characterized by cancer that starts in the urothelial cells that line the inside of the bladder. It is the most common type of bladder cancer.
A urinary system AE that is characterized by yeast in the urine which can range from procurement contamination to a sign of a life-threatening, opportunistic fungal infection.
A bladder AE that is characterized by a severe and long-standing reduction in bladder capacity.

A kidney AE that is characterized by a medical test in which pain is elicited by percussion of the area of the back overlying the kidney (the costovertebral angle, an angle made by the vertebral column and the costal margin).
